</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="73.[151,1436,1119,1216]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,1119,1144]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Definition.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Merejkowsky" authorityYear="1879" box="[287,446,1119,1144]" class="Demospongiae" family="Darwinellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dendroceratida" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Darwinellidae</taxonomicName>
in which the sponge body is always encrusting and the skeleton is composed only of fibres, which are clear of detritus and typically, unbranched (
<figureCitation box="[837,928,1156,1181]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1811,1833]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,193,1790]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 2. Plakortis pulvillus sp. nov. A. Preserved sample; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x 10); D. Diods." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651452/files/figure.png" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). In some species, for example 
<taxonomicName authority="de Laubenfels" authorityName="de Laubenfels" class="Demospongiae" family="Darwinellidae" genus="Aplysilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dendroceratida" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="polyraphis">
<emphasis box="[1284,1436,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">A. polyraphis</emphasis>
de Laubenfels
</taxonomicName>
, branching is frequent.
</paragraph>
